        <h2>Streaming Media and Conferencing Technologies</h2>
        <p>Dr. Lavian offers expert consulting services involving streaming media technologies, audio and video conferencing systems, real-time communications, and multimedia networking. With deep expertise in network protocols and real-time data transport, Dr. Lavian provides expert analysis on complex disputes involving streaming platforms, video conferencing patents, and media delivery technologies.</p>

        <h3>Streaming Media Expert</h3>
        <p>The following are Dr. Tal Lavian's areas of expertise in Streaming Media and Conferencing:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Real-Time Transport Protocol (RTP), RTCP, RTSP, and Real-Time Streaming</li>
          <li>Video Conferencing Systems, WebRTC, SIP, and H.323</li>
          <li>Audio and Video Codecs, Transcoding, and Media Processing</li>
          <li>HTTP Live Streaming (HLS), DASH, and Adaptive Bitrate Streaming</li>
          <li>Content Delivery Networks (CDN) for Media Distribution</li>
          <li>Quality of Service (QoS) and Quality of Experience (QoE) for Media</li>
          <li>VoIP Integration with Video Conferencing Platforms</li>
          <li>Multicast, Broadcast, and Point-to-Point Media Delivery</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Video Conferencing Technologies</h3>
        <p>Video conferencing enables real-time visual communication between two or more parties across different locations. Modern video conferencing systems use a combination of audio and video codecs, signaling protocols, and transport mechanisms to deliver high-quality communication experiences. These systems have become essential for business communications, remote collaboration, and telehealth applications.</p>

        <p>Key technologies include Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) for call setup and management, WebRTC for browser-based real-time communications, and various codec standards (H.264, H.265, VP8, VP9, AV1) for video compression. Video conferencing platforms must handle challenges such as network jitter, packet loss, bandwidth fluctuations, and latency to maintain call quality.</p>

        <h3>Streaming Media Protocols</h3>
        <p>Streaming media delivery relies on specialized protocols designed to transport audio and video content efficiently over IP networks. The Real-Time Transport Protocol (RTP) provides end-to-end delivery services for data with real-time characteristics, such as interactive audio and video. RTCP works alongside RTP to provide feedback on the quality of data distribution.</p>

        <p>Adaptive bitrate streaming technologies such as HTTP Live Streaming (HLS) and Dynamic Adaptive Streaming over HTTP (DASH) have revolutionized how media is delivered over the Internet. These protocols dynamically adjust video quality based on the viewer's network conditions, ensuring smooth playback across varying bandwidth conditions.</p>

        <h3>Audio Technologies</h3>
        <p>Audio streaming and conferencing technologies encompass a wide range of codecs and protocols designed for different use cases. Narrowband codecs such as G.711 and G.729 are used in traditional telephony, while wideband and super-wideband codecs like Opus and AAC provide higher fidelity for music and high-quality voice. Echo cancellation, noise suppression, and automatic gain control are critical signal processing technologies that ensure clear audio in conferencing environments.</p>

        <h3>Media Quality and Performance</h3>
        <p>Ensuring high-quality media delivery requires careful attention to network conditions and media processing. Quality of Service (QoS) mechanisms prioritize media traffic on the network, while Quality of Experience (QoE) metrics measure the end-user perception of media quality. Techniques such as forward error correction, jitter buffering, and bandwidth estimation help maintain consistent media quality even under challenging network conditions.</p>

